    <section id="faq" class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">

        <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
          <button
            class="w-full px-6 py-4 text-left flex items-center justify-between hover:bg-slate-50 transition-colors"
            data-faq-toggle="faq-1"
          >
            <span class="font-semibold text-slate-900 pr-8">How much does basement waterproofing cost in Markham?</span>
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div id="faq-1" class="hidden px-6 pb-4">
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
              Interior waterproofing in Markham costs $140-$260 per linear foot, while exterior waterproofing ranges from $190-$340 per linear foot. Most Markham homes require 40-70 feet of perimeter work, bringing total project costs to $10,000-$22,000 including sump pump systems and backwater valves. Cost varies based on excavation difficulty in clay soils, landscape restoration requirements, and heritage property considerations in areas like Unionville.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
          <button
            class="w-full px-6 py-4 text-left flex items-center justify-between hover:bg-slate-50 transition-colors"
            data-faq-toggle="faq-2"
          >
            <span class="font-semibold text-slate-900 pr-8">Why do newer Markham homes have water problems?</span>
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div id="faq-2" class="hidden px-6 pb-4">
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
              Many Markham subdivisions built in the 1990s-2010s were constructed on former farmland with clay soils and high water tables. Developers often used minimum code-compliant damp proofing instead of comprehensive waterproofing, lot grading has settled over 20-30 years, and the Rouge River watershed creates elevated groundwater pressure during spring melt and heavy rainfall. DrySpace data shows 89% of flooded Markham homes had only spray-on tar damp proofing that fails after 20-30 years, and 72% had settled grading directing water toward foundations.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
          <button
            class="w-full px-6 py-4 text-left flex items-center justify-between hover:bg-slate-50 transition-colors"
            data-faq-toggle="faq-3"
          >
            <span class="font-semibold text-slate-900 pr-8">Is my Tarion warranty applicable for waterproofing issues?</span>
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div id="faq-3" class="hidden px-6 pb-4">
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
              Tarion covers basement waterproofing defects for 2 years after possession and major structural defects for 7 years. However, most Markham homes experiencing flooding today are beyond these warranty periods. If your home is within warranty, document all water intrusion events with photos, dates, and weather conditions, and file claims promptly.
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
              For homes outside warranty periods (most Cornell, Berczy, Milliken homes built 1995-2010), Tarion coverage has expired. You may have legal recourse under Ontario's Limitations Act if you can prove latent defects that should have been discovered during warranty periods but weren't, but this requires legal consultation and is difficult to pursue successfully.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
          <button
            class="w-full px-6 py-4 text-left flex items-center justify-between hover:bg-slate-50 transition-colors"
            data-faq-toggle="faq-4"
          >
            <span class="font-semibold text-slate-900 pr-8">Can I get York Region rebates for waterproofing?</span>
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div id="faq-4" class="hidden px-6 pb-4">
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
              Yes, York Region offers basement flooding protection subsidies covering up to 80% of costs (maximum $3,400) for backwater valve and sump pump installations. Markham homeowners are eligible.
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
              Rebate breakdown: Backwater valve (80% up to $1,750), sump pump system (80% up to $1,250), sewage ejector pump (80% up to $400). Work must be completed by licensed plumber with permit, and application submitted within 120 days.
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
              Additional assistance: Ontario Seniors Home Renovation Tax Credit (up to $1,500/year for seniors 65+) and CMHC Green Home financing (up to $40,000 at preferential rates) can stack with York Region rebates. Total potential savings: $3,000-$8,000 depending on age and project scope.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
          <button
            class="w-full px-6 py-4 text-left flex items-center justify-between hover:bg-slate-50 transition-colors"
            data-faq-toggle="faq-5"
          >
            <span class="font-semibold text-slate-900 pr-8">When is the best time to waterproof in Markham?</span>
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div id="faq-5" class="hidden px-6 pb-4">
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
              Late spring through early fall (May-October) is optimal for exterior waterproofing in Markham. Ground is dry, frost-free, and excavation conditions are ideal. Membrane adhesion requires temperatures above 5°C. Interior waterproofing can be done year-round.
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
              Best scheduling: Book 2-3 months ahead for spring projects (May-June) as demand peaks after spring thaw flooding. July-August availability is typically better. September-October is excellent for exterior work before ground freezes.
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
              Emergency situations: If actively flooding, interior drainage can be installed immediately any time of year to stop water intrusion. Exterior work can follow in warmer months. Don't wait until next spring if you're flooding now.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
          <button
            class="w-full px-6 py-4 text-left flex items-center justify-between hover:bg-slate-50 transition-colors"
            data-faq-toggle="faq-6"
          >
            <span class="font-semibold text-slate-900 pr-8">Should I do interior or exterior waterproofing in Markham?</span>
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div id="faq-6" class="hidden px-6 pb-4">
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
              <strong>Exterior waterproofing</strong> is ideal when: foundation walls have visible cracks or deterioration, original damp proofing has failed, you have good equipment access, and budget allows ($16,000-$24,000). It addresses water at the source by creating a barrier outside the foundation.
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">
              <strong>Interior waterproofing</strong> is preferred when: tight lot access prevents excavation, landscaping preservation is priority, budget is limited ($10,000-$16,000), or water table is so high that exterior-only won't solve it (common in Cornell, Box Grove near Rouge River).
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
              <strong>Both systems</strong> provide redundancy in high-risk areas. DrySpace often recommends exterior waterproofing plus interior drainage in neighborhoods with severe Rouge River watershed influence. This provides defense-in-depth: exterior membrane reduces water volume, interior drainage captures what breaches the envelope.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

